        "text": "*[Bug 18921] New: Parameters in hist(\\dots) passed to plot.histogram throw warnings when passed to title and axis*\n<https:\/\/bugs.r-project.org\/show_bug.cgi?id=18921>\n\n            Bug ID: 18921\n           Summary: Parameters in hist(\\dots) passed to plot.histogram\n                    throw warnings when passed to title and axis\n           Product: R\n           Version: R-devel (trunk)\n          Hardware: All\n                OS: All\n            Status: UNCONFIRMED\n          Severity: trivial\n          Priority: P5\n         Component: Graphics\n          Assignee: <mailto:R-core@R-project.org|R-core@R-project.org>\n          Reporter: <mailto:martin.smith@durham.ac.uk|martin.smith@durham.ac.uk>\n\nPlotting a histogram with `log = \"x\"` causes warnings that \"log\" is not a\ngraphical parameter.\n\nhist(1:100, breaks =2^(0:8), log = \"x\")\n\nThis arises because the `...` argument to `hist()` does not match the `...`\nargument to `plot.histogram`.\n\nThe former reads \"further arguments and graphical parameters passed to\nplot.histogram and thence to `title` and `axis` (if `plot = TRUE`).\"; the\nlatter, \"      \nfurther graphical parameters to `title` and `axis`.\".  \n\nAs `log` is not a formal argument to `plot.histogram`, it is treated as a\ngraphical parameter and thus passed to `title` and `axis`.  In contrast to\nsimilar bugs (<https:\/\/bugs.r-project.org\/show_bug.cgi?id=18108>), I can't see an\nobvious way to accomplish the desired functionality without triggering a\nwarning (I couldn't get a solution with `par(xlog = TRUE)` to work; and\nlog-transforming the data prior to plotting and producing an appropriate axis\nfeels cumbersome and error-prone).\n\nFormally including `log` as a parameter to `plot.histogram` would be a\nseemingly simple fix to this issue.",
